# Host Profile Just Got Smarter: Better KVM Visibility for Capacity Planning

We’ve rolled out a fresh set of updates to **Host Profile** to make it much easier to understand how KVM databases are distributed across hosts, how much capacity is really being used, and where we still have room to grow.

This is especially useful right now as we continue the drive to move **bare-metal PostgreSQL databases to KVM**. As more databases move over, we need better visibility not just into box-level metrics, but also into how database placement, overcommit, and actual resource usage come together on each host.

These new changes are aimed at making that much clearer.

## A better home page view of KVM usage

The Host Profile home page table now gives a much more complete per-host summary of KVM usage.

In addition to the existing host-level information, it now shows:

* **KVM DB count**
* **KVM DB state summary**
* **KVM CPU**
* **KVM Memory**
* **KVM Swap**
* **KVM Disk**

This gives a quick snapshot of how heavily each host is being used by KVM databases and what kind of database mix it is carrying.

Instead of only seeing infrastructure health, we can now also see the database footprint sitting on top of that infrastructure.

## A more holistic view of host load

One of the most useful improvements is that Host Profile now gives a more **holistic view of load and database distribution per host**.

A host may look healthy if you only check CPU or memory, but that is not always enough for good placement decisions. It may already have a high number of KVM databases, too many primaries, or an uneven spread of important workloads.

By bringing together:

* **LoadScore**
* **SharedLoad**
* **KVM DB count**
* **KVM DB states**
* **aggregate KVM CPU, memory, swap, and disk usage**

we get a much better picture of real host pressure.

This helps us answer practical questions like:

* Which hosts are already dense with KVM databases?
* Which hosts are carrying more primaries, standbys, PITR, or snapshot workloads?
* Which hosts still look safe for new placements?
* Which hosts may appear fine on one metric, but are already stretched when viewed more completely?

## Overcommit vs actual usage helps better placement

Another important part of this update is that it becomes easier to compare **allocated capacity vs actual usage**.

For KVM planning, looking at **vCPU overcommit, memory overcommit, and disk overcommit** alongside real usage is very valuable.

That means we can now think about a host in two ways:

* how much has been allocated or committed
* how much is actually being used right now

This matters because a host may still look comfortable on current usage, but already be heavily committed from an allocation point of view. Or the reverse: a host may look highly allocated, but actual usage may show that it still has enough operating headroom for the right kind of placement.

Seeing both sides helps us make safer and smarter decisions for:

* new database placement
* migration planning
* host balancing
* future growth planning

## Dynamic column groups and filters

We’ve also added **dynamic filters for column groups**, so the table can be tailored to the task at hand.

Users can now choose which groups they want to see, such as:

* **Host score**
* **Host metrics**
* **KVM database metrics**

This makes the page much more flexible and easier to use.

For example:

* if you are reviewing general host health, you may want host score and host metrics
* if you are working on database placement or migration planning, you may want to focus on KVM database metrics
* if you want the full picture, you can keep all of them visible together

This is a small UI change, but in practice it makes the table much easier to work with.

## KVM database drill-down per host

Clicking into the KVM database section for a host now opens a dedicated **KVM Databases** view.

This view gives a much clearer breakdown of what is actually running on that host, including:

* total database count
* database state summary
* CPU summary
* memory summary
* disk summary
* snapshot-based visibility over time

This makes it easy to move from a host-level view to a more detailed database-level view without losing context.

It is especially useful when you want to understand why a host is busy, how databases are distributed on it, or whether a host is carrying more important workloads than expected.

## Snapshot visibility for point-in-time review

The KVM database view also includes **snapshots**, which makes it easier to look at host and database details at specific collection times.

This is useful for:

* reviewing recent changes
* comparing resource patterns across snapshots
* checking what the host looked like around a spike or incident
* understanding whether the current state matches the recent trend

That gives Host Profile more operational value beyond just being a static inventory page.

## Easier links into the right operational tools

We’ve also made navigation easier from the KVM database view.

* Clicking on the **database name** takes you to the relevant **PGaaS dashboard / PgMaker**
* Clicking on the **overall load** takes you to **Grafana KVM metrics**

This makes investigations much faster.

Instead of manually searching across multiple tools, you can jump directly from Host Profile into the right place for deeper analysis, whether you want database details in PgMaker or host-level metrics in Grafana.

## Load Projection for planning bigger moves

Another key feature is **Load Projection**.

This is especially helpful when we want to plan operational changes and understand how load would be redistributed before we act.

That includes cases like:

* **per-box rebuilds**
* **datacenter role swaps for compliance**
* **host redistribution exercises**
* **migration planning for bare-metal to KVM**

Load Projection helps us estimate how load will move across selected hosts and what the result may look like after the change.

This helps answer important questions up front:

* Can we do a role swap without disruption?
* Can the remaining hosts safely absorb the redistributed load?
* Do we need additional boxes to handle current demand?
* Do we need more capacity to support future KVM database growth and service deployments?
* Will the new distribution still stay balanced after the move?

That makes Load Projection useful not just for migrations, but also for compliance work, rebuild planning, and general capacity forecasting.

## Why this matters for the bare-metal to KVM drive

As we move more bare-metal PostgreSQL databases onto KVM, placement quality matters more and more.

These Host Profile improvements help us make better decisions by giving us:

* better visibility into database density per host
* clearer state distribution across hosts
* a better understanding of overcommit vs actual usage
* easier drill-down into host and database details
* faster navigation into PgMaker and Grafana
* load projection for future planning

In other words, this is helping Host Profile evolve from a simple host listing into a much more practical tool for **capacity management, placement planning, and operational decision-making**.

## How to use it

A simple way to use the new flow:

Start from the **Host Profile home page** to review host load, shared load, and KVM summaries.

Use the **dynamic filters** to show the column groups most relevant to your task.

Click into a host’s **KVM database section** to see the detailed database-level view for that host.

From there:

* click a **database name** to open **PGaaS / PgMaker**
* click **overall load** to open **Grafana KVM metrics**

And if you are planning a bigger migration, rebuild, or compliance-driven role swap, use **Load Projection** to understand how the environment may look after redistribution.

## Closing thoughts

These updates make Host Profile much more useful and much more actionable.

We now have a friendlier way to see:

* KVM database usage per host
* holistic host pressure
* database distribution
* overcommit vs actual usage
* drill-down details and snapshots
* projected redistribution during bigger operational changes

As KVM continues to grow, this kind of visibility becomes essential for making safer placement decisions and planning capacity with more confidence.

Host Profile is now a much stronger entry point for understanding where our KVM databases are, how our hosts are being used, and how we should plan for what comes next.

